      <div class="insight-card alert">
        <h4>King with Balcony: −28 Nights, −$7,840 Revenue</h4>
        <p>This room type was the single largest volume decline in the portfolio — falling from 83 to 55 nights (−33%) year-over-year. What makes it analytically interesting is that ADR actually increased by $140 to $694, suggesting demand for the room exists and is pricing well when it does book. The volume loss is therefore likely not a rate or demand problem — it's more probably a distribution, restriction, or inventory management issue. Was this room type oversold for certain dates and restricted earlier than other types? Were balcony rooms held back from OTA channels at a higher rate? This deserves a specific audit: pull the King with Balcony availability calendar for March 2025 vs. March 2026.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-card opportunity">
        <h4>The Two Bedroom: $1,024 ADR, Zero Growth — Is There a Rate Ceiling?</h4>
        <p>The Two Bedroom held exactly 75 room nights both years and ADR declined by $3 — a statistically flat result at the portfolio's highest absolute rate. At $1,024 average, this room type is the property's premium anchor. The flat performance could reflect: (1) a natural demand ceiling at the current rate level, (2) this room type selling out quickly in both years leaving no room for optimization, or (3) rate strategy holding flat deliberately as an availability buffer. Either way, the Townhouse heatmap shows forward Two Bedroom and Townhouse dates pricing above $1,100–$1,400 in April and May — which suggests there is rate elasticity available if inventory is managed tightly. Do not let this room type sell too early on high-demand spring dates.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="insight-block">
      <div class="insight-card opportunity">
        <h4>Loft & One Bedroom Deluxe: The Volume Growth Engines</h4>
        <p>These two room types added a combined 44 room nights year-over-year and generated +$29,814 in incremental revenue. The Loft grew from 42 to 63 nights (+50%) at a higher ADR of $625, while the One Bedroom Deluxe grew from 29 to 52 nights (+79%) with slightly softer rate at $691. Both room types now represent important mid-tier contributors filling the gap between the King volume base and the Two Bedroom premium tier. Ensuring these room types have robust distribution across OTA and direct channels heading into spring season is important to sustaining this momentum.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-card caution">
        <h4>The Townhouse: Premium Pricing Potential, Modest Results</h4>
        <p>The Townhouse generated only 17 room nights at $732 ADR — down from 20 nights and $754 ADR a year ago. Yet the forward heatmap shows this room type carrying some of the hotel's highest forward rates, including $1,419 and $1,429 for back-to-back April dates. There is a meaningful disconnect between the forward pricing ambition and the March realized performance. Review whether the Townhouse was effectively marketed and distributed in March, and whether the pricing strategy for this unique product is appropriately calibrated for the compressed demand season that has now arrived.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

