    <!-- KEY INSIGHTS -->
    <div class="insight-block" style="margin-top:28px;">
      <div class="insight-card alert">
        <h4>Cancellation Revenue: A $9,928 YoY Decline That Needs Explaining</h4>
        <p>This is the largest single non-room revenue swing in the dataset and it goes almost entirely in the wrong direction. Cancellation revenue fell from $18,871 to $8,943 — a 52.6% drop. Both years are flagged "Partially rebated," meaning some cancellation fees were waived in both periods, but the gross captured revenue is dramatically lower in 2026.</p>
        <p>There are two possible reads: either fewer guests cancelled in 2026 (which would be operationally positive — lower churn), or the hotel's cancellation policy or enforcement became more lenient, resulting in less revenue being captured per cancellation. Given that total room nights sold were nearly identical (+12 nights), the latter is more likely. This warrants a review of cancellation policy enforcement: are fees being waived more frequently at guest request, and if so, is there a documented service issue driving those waivers?</p>
        <p>The "Partially rebated" tag in MEWS also signals that some portion of cancellation fees collected were subsequently refunded — the gross captured figure is already net of some rebates. Understanding the rebate rate and its change YoY is important context.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-card alert">
        <h4>Guest Credits at 19×: A Service Recovery Signal or Policy Change?</h4>
        <p>Guest credits (comps and service recovery charges) exploded from −$110 in March 2025 to −$2,143 in March 2026. This is not a rounding difference — it is a 19× increase in the dollar amount of credits issued to guests. At a hotel operating at 87.4% occupancy with 697 rooms sold, $2,143 in credits is modest in absolute terms, but the magnitude of the YoY change is a flag that warrants attention.</p>
        <p>Possible causes: (1) a specific service failure or operational issue in March 2026 requiring multiple guest compensations; (2) a new guest satisfaction or service recovery policy that liberalized credit issuance; (3) front desk compensation for the availability restriction exits — guests who couldn't find rooms on their desired dates being compensated with credits for future stays. That third scenario would connect directly to the NAE/RDE booking engine data and would be an important feedback loop to understand and quantify.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="insight-block">
      <div class="insight-card caution">
        <h4>Ancillary Revenue Headwinds: Parking, Transportation, Tours</h4>
        <p>Three ancillary categories declined significantly and together represent about −$6,780 in lost revenue: Parking (−$2,342, −12.8%), Transportation Income (−$935, −53.7%), and Tours & Attractions (−$2,503, −97.1%). The tours figure is especially striking — from $2,578 to $75 is near-complete collapse. This could reflect a program that was discontinued, a vendor relationship that ended, or simply a March 2025 anomaly that inflated that year's figure. Regardless, the combined ancillary revenue picture is softening even as room revenue grows, which means the hotel is becoming more dependent on room revenue as a proportion of total income.</p>
        <p>Other Income also fell 64% (−$3,938), though comparison is complicated by potential category reclassifications between years.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-card caution">
        <h4>F&B: A Real Comparison Is Not Possible Year-Over-Year</h4>
        <p>The 2025 MEWS report consolidates what 2026 reports as separate line items. In 2026, Liquor Sales ($1,644), Wine Sales ($1,659), Soft Beverages ($154), Draft Beer ($12), and Restaurant Gratuity ($1,820) are broken out individually — none of these categories appear in the 2025 report. They were likely included in Food Sales ($7,802) or Other Income ($6,155) in 2025. The net effect: Food Sales appears to decline 35.5% YoY, but this is a reporting artifact, not necessarily an operational decline. To make a true F&B comparison, MEWS should be asked to run the 2025 report with the same level of category granularity as 2026. Until then, total F&B should be treated as not directly comparable.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

