    <div class="insight-block" style="margin-top:28px;">
      <div class="insight-card alert">
        <h4>Quality Score: The Headline Is Hiding the Problem</h4>
        <p>The 9.4 average Quality Score reported in the dashboard is almost entirely a brand campaign artifact. Brand keywords like "the pinch charleston" and "the pinch hotel charleston" naturally score 9–10 because Google sees perfect alignment between the search term, the ad copy, and the landing page. That is expected — not impressive.</p>
        <p>What matters is the QS on campaigns trying to reach people who have never heard of The Pinch. Those tell a different story: Non-Brand Hotel scores 5.5, Non-Brand Best/Charleston scores 5.0, and Non-Brand Downtown scores a concerning 2.0. A QS of 2 means Google has effectively penalized that campaign — it will lose almost every impression-share auction and pay inflated CPCs when it does show. The Downtown campaign's 12 impressions and single click in a full month is the result. These scores also explain part of why the non-brand campaigns are receiving so few impressions despite having budget available: low QS suppresses ad eligibility and rank independent of bid.</p>
        <p><strong>What drives low non-brand QS:</strong> mismatch between keyword intent and ad copy, a generic landing page that doesn't speak to the specific search query (someone searching "best hotel charleston sc" landing on the homepage rather than a page built around that positioning), and low expected click-through rates from historically underperforming ads. All of these are fixable — but they require deliberate creative and landing page work, not just budget increases.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-card caution">
        <h4>The Brand Campaign: Necessary But Over-Fed</h4>
        <p>Brand defense in paid search is legitimate and important for a boutique hotel — Booking.com and Expedia routinely bid on independent property names, and ceding that auction space means paying OTA commission on guests who intended to book direct. Protecting brand search is not the error here.</p>
        <p>The problem is scale. At $6,901 and 75% of total spend, the brand campaign has grown far beyond its defensive purpose. A well-managed brand campaign for a 25-room property in a mid-sized market typically requires $1,500–$3,000/month to maintain strong impression share. Anything beyond that is almost certainly capturing organic intent that would have converted without paid assistance. The $4.09 average CPC on brand terms also suggests active OTA competition for the name — which justifies elevated brand investment relative to a property with no OTA bidding, but not to 75% of budget.</p>
        <p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Cap brand at ~35% of total budget (~$3,200/month). Monitor brand IS% — it currently sits at 83–86%, so a budget cut can be absorbed without meaningful auction loss.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="insight-block">
      <div class="insight-card opportunity">
        <h4>Non-Brand Hotel & Luxury: The Real Story</h4>
        <p>These two campaigns are delivering the account's best returns and they're being systematically starved of budget. Non-Brand Hotel is generating 8.46× ROAS; Non-Brand Luxury is generating 10.68×, the highest of any campaign. Together they received $781 in March and returned $7,231 — a combined ROAS that dwarfs brand's 5.27×.</p>
        <p>The Non-Brand Luxury QS of 7.0 is the strongest among non-brand campaigns, which is helping keep its CPC low at $1.78 — a meaningful cost efficiency advantage. The Non-Brand Hotel QS of 5.5 is more middling; improving it through tighter ad copy and a dedicated landing page could lower its CPC and increase impression eligibility, compounding the benefit of any budget increase.</p>
        <p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Increase combined budget to $3,500–$4,500/month. Before simply scaling spend, invest in QS improvements for Non-Brand Hotel first: write ads that speak directly to "charleston sc hotels" intent and route traffic to a landing page that leads with location, availability, and rate rather than general brand storytelling. A QS improvement from 5.5 to 7+ would reduce effective CPC by roughly 20–25%.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-card alert">
        <h4>Non-Brand Best/Charleston & Downtown: Two Campaigns That Need Surgery</h4>
        <p>The Best/Charleston campaign generated 317 clicks and $639 in spend in March — and $0 in revenue. Its QS of 5.0 signals a meaningful ad relevance or landing page disconnect, and with IS% Lost to Rank at 15.36%, the campaign is regularly losing auctions it should be competing in. Something in the conversion path is broken — either tracking, the landing page, or the keyword set is pulling irrelevant traffic. This needs a full funnel diagnostic before any budget is restored.</p>
        <p>The Downtown campaign is in worse shape: a QS of 2.0 has essentially disqualified it from meaningful competition. It received 12 impressions and 1 click in an entire month — not a budget issue, a quality issue. "Downtown charleston hotels" as a broad match keyword with poor ad relevance means Google has assigned it near-zero expected CTR. This campaign should be rebuilt from scratch: tighter match types, ad copy written specifically for downtown intent, and a clear decision about whether The Pinch's King Street location is actually an advantage worth bidding on.</p>
        <p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Pause Best/Charleston pending audit. Rebuild Downtown as a separate, tightly structured campaign with exact/phrase match only, or discontinue it if the positioning doesn't authentically fit The Pinch's differentiation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

