          <div style="font-size:9.5px; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:0.12em; color:var(--slate-light); margin-bottom:3px;">Vendor Claims</div>
          <div style="font-size:13px; font-weight:500; color:var(--slate);">"March revenue decline was driven by availability and date restrictions — guests were ready to book but couldn't find open dates. This was an inventory issue, not a marketing failure."</div>
        </div>
        <div style="padding:12px 20px;">
          <div style="font-size:9.5px; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:0.12em; color:var(--slate-light); margin-bottom:3px;">Their Evidence</div>
          <div style="font-size:12.5px; color:var(--slate-mid);">March 19–31: 2,118 BE entrances · 591 NAE (No Availability) · 264 RDE (Restricted Date) · 855 total exits = 40.4% couldn't complete a booking</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="padding:18px 20px; font-size:13px; color:var(--slate-mid); line-height:1.75;">
        <strong style="color:var(--slate);">Our Read:</strong> The availability exit data is real, significant, and they deserve credit for surfacing it — the new Hotel Metrics NAE/RDE tracking is genuinely useful. A 40.4% booking failure rate is not normal and does indicate a real supply-side constraint during peak dates.
        <br><br>
        <strong style="color:var(--danger);">However, this framing is also strategically convenient.</strong> The vendor is conflating two different revenue figures. The hotel's PMS-reported room revenue (MEWS) was <strong>up 9% YoY to $444,055</strong> — meaning the hotel performed well overall. The $215,902 figure the vendor cites as "March revenue" is booking-engine web channel revenue only. Those restricted dates filled through other channels (OTAs, travel agents). The vendor is using web channel underperformance to imply March was a bad month — when the full picture is more nuanced. Additionally, the availability restriction data only covers March 19–31 (13 days). What happened in the first 18 days? This gap is unaddressed.
        <br><br>
        <strong style="color:var(--slate);">What to ask:</strong> "What are the specific dates that generated NAE/RDE exits, and are those dates now closed or still open with availability? What is the protocol for pausing paid spend when key dates are fully restricted, so we don't pay to send guests to a dead end?"
