      </li>
      <li class="important">
        <span class="priority-num">4</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Fix the Booking Engine Conversion Funnel — And Stop Paying to Send Guests to a Dead End</strong>
          New booking engine tracking (active from March 19) reveals that 40.4% of booking engine visitors — 855 people in just 13 days — exited without booking due to no availability (591) or restricted dates (264). This is the single most actionable new data point in the March period. Two immediate actions: (1) establish a protocol with Gourmet Marketing to pause or significantly reduce paid search and metasearch spend on dates where availability is restricted or sold out — every click to a dead-end page wastes budget and frustrates a potential guest; (2) review which date restrictions are necessary vs. overly conservative and ensure the booking engine is surfacing alternate available dates proactively rather than showing a blank wall.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="important">
        <span class="priority-num">5</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Investigate Organic Revenue Decline & Website Conversion Gap</strong>
          Organic impressions are down 50% YoY and clicks down 42% — a structural decline that the vendor's MoM recovery narrative obscures. Non-brand organic positions average 14.8 for competitive hotel terms, and "charleston hotels" ranks 16.5, "luxury hotels charleston sc" ranks 9.9 — both far below where a property of this quality should appear. The site-wide CVR declined 14.8% YoY on +27% traffic growth. Conduct a landing page audit: 8,681 sessions hit /lowland with zero bookings, and the homepage (position 1.4% CVR) is the primary converter. Non-homepage landing pages are not converting. The March 21 direct traffic spike (visible in charts) should be identified and its source replicated.
        </div>
      </li>
